04539nam a22005775i 9780773581029DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735810297 a10.1515/97807735810292doi  a(DE-B1597)654679  a(OCoLC)767671757  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a341.5/841 aChalk, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMobilizing the Will to Intervene :bLeadership to Prevent Mass Atrocities /cFrank Chalk, Simon Doyle, Carla Barqueiro, Kyle Matthews. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations and Acronyms -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tMore than Humanitarianism -- tCase Studies of the Rwandan Genocide and the Kosovo Crisis -- tPolicy Recommendations -- tAppendices -- tSummary of W2I Policy Recommendations -- tR2P’s Stringent Criteria Limiting the Use of Force -- tW2I Interview List -- tW2I Team -- tResearch Steering Committee -- tAcademic Consultation Group -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tThe Montreal Institute For Genocide and Human Rights Studies: An Overview0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the handwringing and promises of "never again," the grim recurrences of genocide and crimes against humanity around the world have made it emphatically clear that the international community has been largely ineffective in stopping mass atrocity crimes. Drawing on candid interviews with eighty key figures involved in American and Canadian responses to the Rwandan genocide of 1994 and the Kosovo crisis of 1999, Mobilizing the Will to Intervene explains why and provides a roadmap for change. Since appeals to the "moral law" carry little weight in the political calculations of modern states, the authors argue that civil society must persuade governments that the prevention of mass atrocities around the world is in every country's national interest. In a globalized world, violence, disease, and instability triggered by mass atrocities in one place affect the security, health, and prosperity of all other regions. No nation is an island. Impassioned, insightful, and determined, Mobilizing the Will to Intervene is a direct appeal to American and Canadian politicians, NGOs, journalists, and the public to participate effectively in the prevention of mass atrocities by pressuring their leaders to act. With simple, practical recommendations, this book shows how civil society can participate in preventing future mass atrocities and help repair a ruined system of international aid.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGenocide interventionxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aGenocide interventionxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGenocidexPolitical aspects. 0aGenocidezKosovo (Republic)vCase studies. 0aGenocidezRwandavCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBarqueiro, Carla, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMatthews, Kyle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358102940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773581029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773581029/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles